PHASE 0 — Read Everything First (Serial)
Read lab09-definitions.pdf — know what RSCU, codon bias, and synonymous codons mean before touching code.
Read RSCU_formula.pdf — understand RSCU = O/E, how to compute E, and the category labels (Highly Favored through Highly Disfavored).
Inspect codons.csv — 3 columns: codon sequence, amino acid full name, single-letter code. 64 rows. One row = one CodonEntry.
Inspect both .fasta files — header line starts with >, everything else is raw nucleotides. Strip header, concat lines, uppercase all.

PHASE 1 — Design on Paper First (Serial)
Design CodonEntry — fields: codon sequence, AA name, AA letter, replicase count, spike count, replicase RSCU, spike RSCU.
Map out all Main methods before writing any code: loadCodons(), parseFasta(), splitIntoCodons(), countCodons(), calculateRSCU(), writeCSV(), writeComparison(), writeFavoredReport().

PHASE 2 — Build Foundations (Concurrent — split across teammates)
Teammate 1: Build CodonEntry class — just fields, constructor, getters/setters. No logic yet.
Teammate 2: Write loadCodons() — read codons.csv, split each line, instantiate one CodonEntry per row, add to ArrayList.
Teammate 3: Write parseFasta() + splitIntoCodons() — strip > header, concat + uppercase lines, then loop 3 chars at a time.

PHASE 3 — Counting + RSCU Math (Serial)
Write countCodons() — for each codon string from parseFasta(), find the matching CodonEntry and increment replicaseCount or spikeCount. (Depends on all of Phase 2)
Write calculateRSCU() — group entries by amino acid, compute family total count, apply RSCU = O/E, store result back in CodonEntry. (Depends on 3A)

PHASE 4 — Validate with H1N1 (Serial)
Run your program against H1N1 files — pb1 = replicase equivalent, ha = spike equivalent.
Compare your output to the professor's provided sample files. Match column headers, RSCU values, favored categories, and UP/DOWN logic exactly. Fix everything before moving to COVID data.

PHASE 5 — Generate Output Files (Concurrent)
replicase_rscu.csv — 7 columns: codon, AA name, AA letter, codon count, family total count, percentage, RSCU value.
spike_rscu.csv — same 7 columns, using spike counts.
rscu_comparison.csv — 9 columns: codon, AA name, AA letter, replicase RSCU, spike RSCU, difference (spike − replicase), replicase category, spike category, UP/DOWN.
spike_favored.txt — list UP codons first then DOWN codons; each entry has codon, amino acid, replicase category, spike category.

PHASE 6 — Finalize and Submit (Serial)
